  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How do mushrooms support the immune system?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Medicinal mushrooms contain beta-glucans — complex polysaccharides that activate the innate immune system by binding to receptors on immune cells (macrophages, dendritic cells, natural killer cells). When beta-glucans bind to Dectin-1 and Complement Receptor 3 (CR3) on immune cells, they trigger a cascade of immune activation: macrophages increase phagocytosis (pathogen engulfment), natural killer cells enhance cytotoxicity (ability to destroy virus-infected and abnormal cells), dendritic cells improve antigen presentation (enabling the adaptive immune system to recognize and target specific threats), and cytokine production increases to coordinate the overall immune response. This immunomodulatory effect is not overstimulation — beta-glucans prime the immune system for more effective response without causing chronic inflammation. Turkey tail and reishi have the most clinical evidence for immune enhancement.' } },
